# Interfaces: Deep Dive — Default Methods, Static Methods, Private Methods, and Functional Design

## Interface Evolution with Default Methods (Java 8)
Before Java 8, adding a method to an interface broke every implementing class. Default methods solve this — they provide a default implementation that all existing implementers inherit:

```java
public interface Collection<E> {
    // Existing abstract method
    boolean add(E e);

    // New in Java 8 — default method added without breaking existing implementations
    default void addAll(Collection<? extends E> c) {
        for (E e : c) add(e);
    }

    default Stream<E> stream() {
        return StreamSupport.stream(spliterator(), false);
    }
}
```
This is how Java 8 added `stream()`, `forEach()`, and `removeIf()` to Collection without breaking every existing custom collection.

## Conflict Resolution When Two Interfaces Provide Same Default
```java
interface A { default String hello() { return "Hello from A"; } }
interface B { default String hello() { return "Hello from B"; } }

class C implements A, B {
    @Override
    public String hello() {
        return A.super.hello(); // explicit resolution required — compiler error if omitted
    }
}
```
Rule: class always wins over interface default; more specific interface wins over less specific; if tie — must override.

## Static Methods in Interfaces (Java 8)
Interface static methods are utility helpers tied to the interface. They are NOT inherited:
```java
public interface Validator<T> {
    boolean validate(T value);

    static <T> Validator<T> of(Predicate<T> predicate) {
        return predicate::test; // static factory — creates Validator from Predicate
    }

    static Validator<String> nonBlank() {
        return s -> s != null && !s.isBlank();
    }
}

Validator<String> check = Validator.nonBlank();
check.validate("hello"); // true
// Cannot call subclass.nonBlank() — static methods on interfaces are not inherited
```

## Private Methods in Interfaces (Java 9)
Private methods avoid code duplication between multiple default methods:
```java
public interface AuditableRepository<T, ID> {
    T save(T entity);
    void delete(ID id);

    default T saveWithAudit(T entity, String userId) {
        T saved = save(entity);
        logAudit("SAVE", userId); // private helper
        return saved;
    }

    default void deleteWithAudit(ID id, String userId) {
        delete(id);
        logAudit("DELETE", userId); // reused private helper
    }

    private void logAudit(String action, String userId) {
        System.out.printf("AUDIT: %s by %s at %s%n", action, userId, Instant.now());
    }
}
```

## Interface Constant — A Pattern to Avoid
```java
// ANTI-PATTERN: Interface as constant holder
public interface OrderConstants {
    int MAX_ITEMS = 100;     // implicitly public static final
    String DEFAULT_CURRENCY = "USD";
}
// Classes implement OrderConstants just to inherit the constants — pollutes the class hierarchy

// CORRECT: Use a final class with private constructor
public final class OrderConstants {
    private OrderConstants() {}
    public static final int MAX_ITEMS = 100;
    public static final String DEFAULT_CURRENCY = "USD";
}
```

## Sealed Interfaces (Java 17)
Sealed interfaces restrict which classes can implement them — useful when you want exhaustive pattern matching:
```java
public sealed interface Shape permits Circle, Rectangle, Triangle {}

public record Circle(double radius) implements Shape {}
public record Rectangle(double width, double height) implements Shape {}
public record Triangle(double base, double height) implements Shape {}

// switch is exhaustive — compiler knows all implementations
double area = switch (shape) {
    case Circle c    -> Math.PI * c.radius() * c.radius();
    case Rectangle r -> r.width() * r.height();
    case Triangle t  -> 0.5 * t.base() * t.height();
}; // no default needed — compiler proves all cases covered
```

## Interface vs Abstract Class — The Practical Decision
Use **interface** when:
- Defining a capability that unrelated classes share (Printable, Serializable, Comparable, Runnable)
- You need multiple inheritance of type
- The contract has no shared state

Use **abstract class** when:
- There is shared implementation AND shared mutable state
- You want to control construction (protected constructor pattern)
- Some methods should be `final` (template method pattern)

## Common Mistakes
1. **Fat interface:** `UserService extends CRUD, Reporting, Auditing, Emailing` — one interface for 30 methods. Split by ISP.
2. **Interface with only constants:** the Constant Interface antipattern. Use a final utility class.
3. **`default` for core logic:** default methods should provide OPTIONAL behavior or backward-compatible additions, not the primary implementation.
4. **Forgetting conflict resolution:** implementing two interfaces with the same default method signature compiles only if you override it in the class.

